1
00:02:40,800 --> 00:02:42,439
Two large Bushmills please, darling.

2
00:03:32,260 --> 00:03:33,488
Do you want another drink?

3
00:03:37,542 --> 00:03:38,770
I'll buy you.

4
00:04:45,007 --> 00:04:47,398
What's happening ?

5
00:04:47,648 --> 00:04:49,560
- Get in.
- Alright

6
00:04:52,330 --> 00:04:53,922
- Inside.

7
00:07:00,658 --> 00:07:02,218
Harold will be well pleased.

8
00:07:02,460 --> 00:07:04,610
- When is he back?
- Today.

9
00:07:05,941 --> 00:07:07,454
Highly confidential.

10
00:07:07,702 --> 00:07:10,500
I need them tomorrow,
for a counsel meeting.

11
00:07:11,263 --> 00:07:13,698
No sweat, I'll get them photo-copied.

12
00:07:14,224 --> 00:07:16,057
And the Americans?

13
00:07:17,106 --> 00:07:19,495
- I'll reckon they're coming.
- Good.

14
00:07:19,746 --> 00:07:23,457
- About the nosh: on the corporation?
- Of course, counsellor.

15
00:07:25,068 --> 00:07:27,139
- See you, Jeff.
- See you.

16
00:08:09,885 --> 00:08:11,205
Wait a minute!

17
00:09:02,185 --> 00:09:05,304
These are plans, he needs them
back by this afternoon.

18
00:09:05,546 --> 00:09:06,946
Good old George.

19
00:09:08,148 --> 00:09:10,742
- Everything alright while I was away?
- Yeah.

20
00:09:11,109 --> 00:09:12,907
The new casino has gone through.

21
00:09:13,430 --> 00:09:16,423
- No problems?
- No, everything's alright.

22
00:09:17,832 --> 00:09:19,629
Did anyone guess where I was?

23
00:09:20,072 --> 00:09:22,951
Alan reckoned a health farm.

24
00:09:23,754 --> 00:09:26,188
One or two rumours about New York.

25
00:09:26,475 --> 00:09:28,750
- But nobody guessed?
- No.

26
00:10:02,608 --> 00:10:05,919
Should have left 10 minutes ago,
I'm late for church.

27
00:10:07,250 --> 00:10:09,208
I hate being late for church.

28
00:10:10,931 --> 00:10:12,080
There you are.

29
00:10:13,333 --> 00:10:15,801
Bye bye, have a nice Easter.

30
00:10:18,295 --> 00:10:20,604
God rot your soul.

31
00:10:40,903 --> 00:10:43,782
Oh Christ Harold she's always with us
when she goes to church.

32
00:10:45,225 --> 00:10:47,820
She's got really religious in her
old age, hasn't she?

33
00:10:48,306 --> 00:10:50,582
Church 3 times a day, it's Good Friday.

34
00:10:50,827 --> 00:10:52,146
Have a Bloody Mary.

35
00:10:52,587 --> 00:10:55,661
She thinks Paula is an angel
and I'm the devil in disguise.

36
00:10:56,069 --> 00:11:00,622
Ah well, me and Paula have only been divorced
for 10 years, give her a chance to get used to it.

37
00:11:01,351 --> 00:11:02,671
Cheers.

38
00:11:03,071 --> 00:11:06,223
- Have you organised everything?
- Yes, it's coming along.

39
00:11:08,153 --> 00:11:10,270
Charlie should be landing about now.

40
00:11:11,794 --> 00:11:13,194
Here.

41
00:11:14,237 --> 00:11:17,946
- Maybe we should have gone to the airport to meet him.
- Nah, play it cool.

42
00:11:18,598 --> 00:11:22,797
When the governor of Coca-Cola drops in to London
the Queen don't go dashing off to Heathrow, does she?

43
00:11:23,760 --> 00:11:26,035
- Queen?
- Well you know what I mean.

44
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:27,714
All plated up, right?

45
00:11:27,962 --> 00:11:30,681
He went to school with princess Ann,
played hockey with her, all that.

46
00:11:30,922 --> 00:11:34,963
- It's lacrosse at Benenden, hockey's frightfully vulgar.
- Yes, yes plenty of, yeah.

47
00:11:35,644 --> 00:11:37,363
The Yanks love snobbery.

48
00:11:37,605 --> 00:11:41,361
They really feel they've arrived in England
if the upper classes treat them like shit.

49
00:11:41,767 --> 00:11:44,406
- Gives them a sense of history.

50
00:11:45,408 --> 00:11:47,445
We'd better check how the chef's progressing.

51
00:11:48,009 --> 00:11:50,160
That geezer don't half know about grub.

52
00:11:50,930 --> 00:11:54,606
The smells that have been coming up from the galley
all morning have been driving me potty.

53
00:11:55,051 --> 00:11:56,451
You lay off the vodka.

54
00:12:01,694 --> 00:12:03,845
- It's going well?
- Madam, look at this.

55
00:12:04,215 --> 00:12:08,335
These blue plates with these
white plates, it's ridiculous.

56
00:12:14,219 --> 00:12:16,096
Now that's a right horrible ponce.

57
00:12:16,659 --> 00:12:18,491
The polly's French isn't he?

58
00:12:19,061 --> 00:12:21,017
It's really splendid.

59
00:12:21,621 --> 00:12:23,978
We thank you very much.

60
00:12:24,903 --> 00:12:26,416
Very nice.

61
00:12:26,663 --> 00:12:29,053
These French geezers really know their stuff, eh?

62
00:12:29,305 --> 00:12:32,503
- Are they new?
- Bought 'em yesterday, 20 quid a piece.

63
00:12:33,546 --> 00:12:36,061
I bet Harold was reluctant
to take the labels off, eh?

64
00:12:36,307 --> 00:12:39,141
He broke two of them demonstrating
their exquisite delicacy.

65
00:12:40,428 --> 00:12:42,068
He doesn't know his own strength.

66
00:12:45,790 --> 00:12:48,147
Have you sorted out Immigration for the Yank?

67
00:12:48,392 --> 00:12:51,704
- Yeah Parky's dealt with that.
- Then you may go and have a drink on deck.

68
00:14:47,758 --> 00:14:49,111
Hello, are you alright?

69
00:14:49,358 --> 00:14:50,951
Having a good time?

70
00:14:51,279 --> 00:14:52,713
Enjoy yourselves.

71
00:14:54,040 --> 00:14:55,359
Counsellors.

72
00:14:55,600 --> 00:14:56,829
Excuse me I won't keep him.

73
00:14:58,362 --> 00:15:01,275
Those plans came in very handy
my son, much obliged.

74
00:15:01,963 --> 00:15:03,112
No sweat, Harold.

75
00:15:03,364 --> 00:15:06,802
- The license on the casino,
did that go through alright, no problems?
- A slight problem.

76
00:15:07,045 --> 00:15:09,685
- How's that?
- Counsellor Taylor seems to think you're a gangster.

77
00:15:11,127 --> 00:15:14,882
- What's the SP on the American?
- Just pump him full of information, everything you've got.

78
00:15:15,127 --> 00:15:18,087
- Instant planning permission, all that sort of chat?
- Yeah.

79
00:15:18,369 --> 00:15:21,168
The Yanks think we're a cock handed corner shop over here.

80
00:15:21,410 --> 00:15:23,129
Exhume the fishes, right?

81
00:15:23,411 --> 00:15:26,450
I'll tell him I quickly mind an enterprise that should appeal?

82
00:15:29,213 --> 00:15:31,489
Parky, you're not drinking?

83
00:15:31,975 --> 00:15:34,091
Harold you know I only drink when I'm on duty.

84
00:15:34,376 --> 00:15:36,412
- How's business, alright?
- A drizzle of complaints.

85
00:15:36,656 --> 00:15:38,090
You get a lot of that in your game, eh?

86
00:15:39,177 --> 00:15:40,452
Hello, Dave.

87
00:15:40,698 --> 00:15:43,736
- How are you, last time I saw you, you had spots.
- Thanks very much.

88
00:15:44,219 --> 00:15:46,369
Even I notice the coppers are getting younger now.

89
00:15:46,620 --> 00:15:49,419
- He's a detective sergeant now Harold.
- Is he?

90
00:15:49,741 --> 00:15:51,255
Celebration, come here.

91
00:15:51,862 --> 00:15:53,182
Champagne my son.

92
00:15:53,543 --> 00:15:54,817
Here's to you.

93
00:15:55,143 --> 00:15:57,373
Nice seeing real friends doing well.

94
00:15:58,345 --> 00:15:59,744
Here's to real friends.

95
00:15:59,985 --> 00:16:01,464
Hi George.

96
00:16:03,466 --> 00:16:04,695
Jeff.

97
00:16:04,947 --> 00:16:06,175
Won't be a minute.

98
00:16:08,548 --> 00:16:12,987
Keep your eyes on the boy's behaviour, will you?
I don't want any of 'em acting like delinquents.

99
00:16:13,230 --> 00:16:15,381
No chance, they know it's important.

100
00:16:15,710 --> 00:16:17,703
I told 'em to put their wedding suits on.

101
00:16:19,233 --> 00:16:20,790
I think you're gonna like Charlie.

102
00:16:21,073 --> 00:16:22,473
So what's the plan?

103
00:16:22,714 --> 00:16:24,033
A cocktail here so we can clog the marina,

104
00:16:24,274 --> 00:16:28,064
then off down river so they can see
the scope of the whole project.

105
00:16:28,396 --> 00:16:31,275
- Have you fixed the moorings?
- It's all under control.

106
00:16:31,598 --> 00:16:33,077
Another thing...

107
00:16:33,837 --> 00:16:36,194
Harris has got a lot of talking to do
this afternoon...

108
00:16:36,519 --> 00:16:39,717
...can you keep him off the booze?
Top him off with Perrier water or something.

109
00:16:41,041 --> 00:16:42,794
Harold, he's here.

110
00:16:43,041 --> 00:16:45,033
You two pipe him aboard and I'll be up, right?

111
00:16:52,805 --> 00:16:54,126
I can't believe you.

112
00:16:57,326 --> 00:17:00,638
- The kid from New Yersey, eh?
- The boy from Stepney.

113
00:17:01,368 --> 00:17:03,247
Charlie, have some champagne.

114
00:17:04,090 --> 00:17:07,207
You should be the captain of this boat,
great timing.

115
00:17:07,572 --> 00:17:09,369
Listen I wanna propose a toast.

116
00:17:09,772 --> 00:17:12,652
- Hands across the ocean, right?
- To the future.

117
00:17:12,893 --> 00:17:14,293
To the future here.

118
00:17:15,654 --> 00:17:18,852
Harold, I don't think you met Tony,
when you were over there?

119
00:17:19,095 --> 00:17:21,087
- Tony?
- My lawyer.

120
00:17:21,336 --> 00:17:24,409
- Mr. Shand, Tony.
- Very nice to meet you.

121
00:17:25,978 --> 00:17:30,097
- Charlie, Tony would you like to come and meet some people now?
- Good.

122
00:17:30,339 --> 00:17:32,012
They're important, but they're nice. Come on.

123
00:17:35,261 --> 00:17:37,139
Keep your eye on that Tony.

124
00:17:37,582 --> 00:17:39,938
He never said he was gonna bring anybody.

125
00:17:40,583 --> 00:17:42,734
They always come in two's, like the bailiffs.

126
00:17:43,185 --> 00:17:44,858
Means they mean business.

127
00:18:40,767 --> 00:18:41,882
Hola.

128
00:18:43,647 --> 00:18:44,922
Hi.

129
00:19:23,183 --> 00:19:26,380
"Happy are those who are called to His supper"

130
00:19:26,704 --> 00:19:30,220
"Lord I am not worthy to receive You"

131
00:19:30,466 --> 00:19:33,265
"but only say the word and I shall be healed."

132
00:19:56,116 --> 00:19:57,389
My God!

133
00:19:57,636 --> 00:19:58,910
Ladies and gentlemen.

134
00:20:07,280 --> 00:20:09,111
I'm not a politician.

135
00:20:10,601 --> 00:20:14,562
I'm a businessman with a sense of history.

136
00:20:14,882 --> 00:20:16,760
And I'm also a Londoner,

137
00:20:17,163 --> 00:20:23,355
and today is a day of great historical
significance for London.

138
00:20:25,086 --> 00:20:27,681
Our country is not an island anymore.

139
00:20:28,728 --> 00:20:31,960
We're a leading European state.

140
00:20:32,930 --> 00:20:37,049
And I believe that this is the decade,

141
00:20:37,291 --> 00:20:42,447
in which London will become Europe's capital.

142
00:20:42,974 --> 00:20:45,807
Having cleared away the outdated,

143
00:20:46,374 --> 00:20:50,369
we've got mile after mile and
acre after acre of land,

144
00:20:51,056 --> 00:20:53,446
for our future prosperity.

145
00:20:54,897 --> 00:20:57,288
No other city in the world...

146
00:20:57,739 --> 00:21:01,700
has got right in its centre,
such an opportunity...

147
00:21:02,300 --> 00:21:04,690
for profitable progress.

148
00:21:05,222 --> 00:21:08,852
So it's important that the right people...

149
00:21:10,664 --> 00:21:13,303
mastermind the new London.

150
00:21:14,626 --> 00:21:20,419
Proven people, with nerve,
knowledge and expertise.

151
00:21:22,828 --> 00:21:25,549
That, ladies and gentlemen,

152
00:21:27,150 --> 00:21:29,665
is why you are all here today.

153
00:21:31,711 --> 00:21:34,068
All trusted friends.

154
00:21:35,873 --> 00:21:40,551
and why Charlie and Tony are here today,
our American friends,

155
00:21:41,755 --> 00:21:45,989
to endorse the global nature of this venture.

156
00:21:47,878 --> 00:21:49,516
Let's hear it ladies and gentlemen.

157
00:21:51,199 --> 00:21:53,589
Hands across the ocean.

158
00:22:04,124 --> 00:22:06,686
There used to be 80 or 90 ships in here at one time.

159
00:22:07,046 --> 00:22:09,082
They used to queue up to get in...

160
00:22:09,646 --> 00:22:12,799
all the way up to Galleon's Reach
right down to Tilbury.

161
00:22:14,608 --> 00:22:17,328
Used to be the greatest docks in
the world at one time, this.

162
00:22:18,129 --> 00:22:20,281
Things change Harold, don't get nostalgic.

163
00:22:21,091 --> 00:22:22,524
Look to the future.

164
00:22:22,771 --> 00:22:25,127
You realise you're 35 minutes away from Europe?

165
00:22:25,853 --> 00:22:27,445
Great potential.

166
00:22:27,693 --> 00:22:29,287
I live in a new country,

167
00:22:29,534 --> 00:22:32,732
and I respect the past, but always
keep my eye on the future.

168
00:22:36,576 --> 00:22:38,375
Don't touch, I'll take care of that.

169
00:22:46,540 --> 00:22:48,931
You've got to go to sleep Charlie,
we've got a tight schedule.

170
00:22:49,301 --> 00:22:51,691
I want you to meet my property lawyers, the best...

171
00:22:51,942 --> 00:22:55,174
and then there's an accountant who
specialises in gambling tax.

172
00:22:55,424 --> 00:22:58,178
This isn't a horse race,
don't rush me Harold.

173
00:22:58,425 --> 00:23:00,256
Then there's someone you've got to meet.

174
00:23:00,506 --> 00:23:04,182
Harold I said don't rush me,
I hate tight schedules.

175
00:23:04,907 --> 00:23:08,457
I've got everything covered that I
have to cover, but in my own time.

176
00:23:11,030 --> 00:23:13,464
We're just docking now, it will be
nice and quiet if you want to sleep.

177
00:23:14,951 --> 00:23:18,343
Come on Harold, let's leave Charlie
alone for a while.

178
00:23:29,076 --> 00:23:31,033
Bad luck putting the hat on the bed.

179
00:23:32,678 --> 00:23:35,671
Relax, he'll be alright.

180
00:23:36,199 --> 00:23:38,999
Yeah, poor old sod is tired.

181
00:24:09,012 --> 00:24:10,969
Look out for the boys in blue.

182
00:24:21,377 --> 00:24:22,730
Yeah?

183
00:24:24,738 --> 00:24:26,138
Yeah.

184
00:24:29,420 --> 00:24:30,900
What?

185
00:24:37,863 --> 00:24:39,262
Right.

186
00:24:48,266 --> 00:24:49,747
This is...

187
00:24:51,348 --> 00:24:53,499
diabolical.

188
00:24:55,709 --> 00:24:56,938
What is it?

189
00:24:58,152 --> 00:25:00,541
Blown up, he's dead.

190
00:25:02,672 --> 00:25:05,312
Eric is dead, a car bomb.

191
00:25:07,875 --> 00:25:10,548
My mother's alright, she's suffering from shock,
she's in the London Hospital.

192
00:25:11,996 --> 00:25:13,224
I don't understand.

193
00:25:14,236 --> 00:25:16,832
You need a million dollar computer
to understand this.

194
00:25:17,879 --> 00:25:21,668
Who'd do such a thing, it's outrageous.
Outside a church...

195
00:25:22,040 --> 00:25:25,238
you don't go crucifying people outside
a church on Good Friday.

196
00:25:25,481 --> 00:25:28,361
- What's the matter Harold?
- Eric's been blown up.

197
00:25:29,723 --> 00:25:31,634
- A bomb?
- Yeah in the Rolls.

198
00:25:32,884 --> 00:25:35,079
- I don't believe it, when?
- Just now.

199
00:25:35,725 --> 00:25:38,718
Mother's in hospital suffering from shock,
I'm not surprised.

200
00:25:39,367 --> 00:25:41,643
She went to church to say her prayers,
not to get blown up.

201
00:25:41,928 --> 00:25:45,717
- But why?
- Someone tried to discredit you in front of...

202
00:25:46,009 --> 00:25:47,728
The Yanks?

203
00:25:49,090 --> 00:25:51,686
No, nobody knew, did they?

204
00:25:52,132 --> 00:25:54,522
- Well they mustn't find out.
- They're sleeping.

205
00:25:54,772 --> 00:25:59,530
Right, I want everybody in the corporation
working on this, fast!

206
00:25:59,774 --> 00:26:01,254
And I want Colin here.

207
00:26:01,494 --> 00:26:03,646
Where is he? He should have been here.
Where is he?

208
00:26:03,976 --> 00:26:05,489
- He went swimming.
- Swimming?

209
00:26:06,056 --> 00:26:07,376
He should have been here.

210
00:26:07,617 --> 00:26:10,178
Right, I want everyone working.

211
00:26:10,419 --> 00:26:13,058
Razors, you round them all up
and get them moving, fast.

212
00:26:13,300 --> 00:26:16,736
Right, keep them on their toes because
I want this settled, tonight.

213
00:26:19,221 --> 00:26:21,053
And you'd better see your mother.

214
00:26:23,223 --> 00:26:24,623
Yeah.

215
00:26:25,664 --> 00:26:30,739
Listen, if anyone hears anything, anything at all,
I'll be at the Mayfair casino, right?

216
00:26:34,547 --> 00:26:36,426
It's the work of a maniac.

217
00:26:40,870 --> 00:26:43,590
I'll have his carcass dripping blood by midnight.

218
00:27:20,205 --> 00:27:21,604
More bad news...

219
00:27:22,806 --> 00:27:24,000
...Colin.

220
00:27:24,246 --> 00:27:26,044
- Colin?
- Yeah.

221
00:27:26,887 --> 00:27:28,401
He's dead.

222
00:28:28,708 --> 00:28:30,938
I did my national service with Colin

223
00:28:32,909 --> 00:28:34,980
We did 6 months in the glasshouse together.

224
00:28:35,670 --> 00:28:40,222
Two kids of 18, 6 months. They put us right
through it the bastards.

225
00:28:44,273 --> 00:28:46,742
Salisbury Plain manoeuvres.

226
00:28:47,794 --> 00:28:50,992
Used to hump this bleedin' great wireless about.

227
00:28:54,516 --> 00:28:58,715
One window, snow, blizzards,

228
00:28:58,958 --> 00:29:00,709
freezing the bollocks off the ponies.

229
00:29:01,478 --> 00:29:02,832
I got lost.

230
00:29:03,519 --> 00:29:06,432
In them days you stayed lost,
until they nicked you for being AWOL.

231
00:29:08,361 --> 00:29:11,354
And Colin, on a 24 hour pass,

232
00:29:13,282 --> 00:29:15,400
he came out looking for me on his own.

233
00:29:16,644 --> 00:29:18,874
It's lucky he found me or I
would've froze to death.

234
00:29:20,526 --> 00:29:21,878
Yeah.

235
00:29:23,326 --> 00:29:25,441
Colin never hurt a fly...

236
00:29:27,368 --> 00:29:29,484
...well only when it was necessary.

237
00:29:30,368 --> 00:29:33,646
It was always clean, never anything
malicious about Colin.

238
00:29:34,210 --> 00:29:36,770
- Why size him up?
- On my grief.

239
00:29:37,009 --> 00:29:38,524
Sorry, H.

240
00:29:45,094 --> 00:29:47,085
Me and Colin was very close.

241
00:29:49,174 --> 00:29:51,405
I've known him since we was at school.

242
00:29:55,336 --> 00:29:56,736
What's going on?

243
00:30:00,258 --> 00:30:03,092
They try and blow up me mum,
wipe out me best mate...

244
00:30:04,499 --> 00:30:06,252
What are they trying to do?

245
00:30:06,620 --> 00:30:09,010
Put the frighteners on me, wind me up, what?

246
00:30:17,504 --> 00:30:18,732
Harold,

247
00:30:19,544 --> 00:30:23,744
I've kept it all incognito, they're gonna
collect the body in an ice cream van.

248
00:30:24,146 --> 00:30:28,026
There's a lot of dignity in that, isn't there?
Going out like a raspberry ripple.

249
00:30:28,267 --> 00:30:31,340
They're gonna store the body in the
